@article{Valdes2020,
abstract = {7 Benthic oxygen isotope records are commonly used as a proxy for global mean surface temperatures 8 during the late Cretaceous and Cenozoic, and the resulting estimates have been extensively used in 9 characterising major trends and transitions in the climate system, and for analysing past climate 10 sensitivity. However, some fundamental assumptions governing this proxy have rarely been tested. 11 Two key assumptions are: (a) benthic foraminiferal temperatures are geographically well mixed and 12 are linked to surface high latitude temperatures, and (b) surface high latitude temperatures are well 13 correlated with global mean temperatures. To investigate the robustness of these assumptions 14 through geological time, we performed a series of 109 climate model simulations using a unique set 15 of paleogeographical reconstructions covering the entire Phanerozoic at the stage-level. The 16 simulations have been run for at least 5000 model years to ensure that the deep ocean is in dynamic 17 equilibrium. We find that the correlation between deep ocean temperatures and global mean 18 surface temperatures is good for the Cenozoic and thus the proxy data are reliable indicators for this 19 time period, albeit with a standard error of 2K. This uncertainty has not normally been assessed and 20 needs to be combined with other sources of uncertainty when, for instance, estimating climate 21 sensitivity based on using $\delta$ 18 O measurements from benthic foraminifera. The correlation between 22 deep and global mean surface temperature becomes weaker for pre-Cenozoic time periods (when 23 the paleogeography is significantly different than the present-day). The reasons for the weaker 24 correlation includes variability in the source region of the deep water (varying hemispheres but also 25 varying latitudes of sinking), the depth of ocean overturning (some extreme warm climates have 26 relatively shallow and sluggish circulations weakening the link between surface and deep ocean), 27 and the extent of polar amplification (e.g. ice albedo feedbacks). Deep ocean sediments prior to the 28 Cretaceous are rare, so extending the benthic foram proxy further into deeper time is problematic, 29 but the model results presented here would suggest that the predicted deep ocean temperatures 30 would probably be unreliable. 31},
