@article{Beals1923,
abstract = {Eddy-permitting simulations are used to show that basin-like gyres can be observed in 6 the large scale barotropic flow of a wind-driven channel with a meridional topographic ridge. 7 This is confirmed using both 2-layer quasi-geostrophic and 25-level primitive equation models 8 at high horizontal resolution. Comparing results from simulations with and without the 9 topographic ridge, it is shown that the zonal baroclinic transport in the channel increases 10 with increasing wind stress when the bottom topography is flat, but not when there is a 11 meridional ridge. The saturation of transport for increasing wind occurs in conjunction with 12 the development of recirculating gyres in the large scale barotropic streamfunction. This 13 suggests that the total circulation can be thought of as a superposition of a gyre mode 14 (which has zero circumpolar transport) and a free circumpolar mode (which contains all 15 of the transport). Basin-like gyres arise in the channel, because the topography steers the 16 barotropic streamlines and supports a frictional boundary layer similar to the more familiar 17 ones observed along western boundaries. The gyre mode is thus closely linked with the 18 bottom form stress exerted by the along ridge flow and provides the sink for the wind 19 momentum input. In this framework, any increase in wind forcing spins a stronger gyre as 20 opposed to feeding the circumpolar transport. This hypothesis is supported with a suite of 21 experiments where key parameters are carried over a wide range: wind stress, wind stress 22 curl, ridge height, channel length, and bottom friction.},
